del_air <- as_tibble(read_delim(filenames[2],show_col_types = FALSE))
fed_ex <- as_tibble(read_delim(filenames[3],show_col_types = FALSE))
un_air <- as_tibble(read_delim(filenames[4],show_col_types = FALSE))

2) Merge the four data tibble in a common tibble¶

In [4]:
# Add to each tibble a column with the company's name, then perform inner-join
am_air<- am_air %>% add_column(CompanyName = rep(companies[[1]], nrow(am_air)))
del_air <- del_air %>% add_column(CompanyName = rep(companies[[2]], nrow(am_air)))
fed_ex <- fed_ex %>% add_column(CompanyName = rep(companies[[3]], nrow(am_air)))
un_air <- un_air %>% add_column(CompanyName = rep(companies[[4]], nrow(am_air)))

#Merge using innerjoin. Now total contains the complete tibble
total <- rbind(am_air,del_air,fed_ex,un_air)

4) When did each company reach the minimum and maximum number of employees?¶

In [8]:
#Add a column with total number of employees
total <- total %>% add_column(Total = total$"Full-time" + total$"Part-time")
In [9]:
#Store times of minima and maxima
minimaTimes <- c()
maximaTimes <- c()

#Check for each company
for(company in companies){
    minimaTimes <- c(minimaTimes, toString(total[total$CompanyName == company, ]$"Time"[which.min(total[total$CompanyName == company, ]$"Total")]))
    maximaTimes <- c(maximaTimes, toString(total[total$CompanyName == company, ]$"Time"[which.max(total[total$CompanyName == company, ]$"Total")]))
}

6) Did the COVID-19 pandemic have any influence in the employed workers of the airline companies? Can you see a trend in the years 2019-2023?¶

The number of full-time employees of American Airline, Delta Airline and United Airline experienced a sharp drop at the beginning of 2020. FedEx was an exception, perhaps because it is a cargo airline, whereas the other companies specialize in passenger flights. The companies which lost full-time employees in 2020 started regaining employees in the following years.

#For each week number, compute average over days 1:5 (work days) and {0,6} (weekend)
weeklyMeans <- aggregate(flightCount$n, list(week = flightCount$week, workday = flightCount$weekDay >= 1 & flightCount$weekDay <=5, origin = flightCount$origin), mean)

#To have the average number of flights, regardless of the airport, we sum across the origin
weeklyMeans <- aggregate(weeklyMeans$x, list(week = weeklyMeans$week, workday = weeklyMeans$workday), sum)

#There are some NA values in dep_delay, so we have to apply min and max with the na.rm option set to TRUE.

#Min, max and mean delay
mins <- aggregate(flights$dep_delay, list(date = flights$date, origin = flights$origin), function(x) return(min(x,na.rm=TRUE)))
maxs <- aggregate(flights$dep_delay, list(date = flights$date, origin = flights$origin), function(x) return(max(x,na.rm=TRUE)))
means <- aggregate(flights$dep_delay, list(date = flights$date, origin = flights$origin), function(x) return(mean(x,na.rm=TRUE)))

for(airport in origins){
    p <- ggplot()
    line_min <- geom_line(mins[mins$origin==airport,], mapping = aes(x=mins[mins$origin==airport,]$date, y=mins[mins$origin==airport,]$x, color = "Min"))
    line_max <- geom_line(maxs[mins$origin==airport,], mapping = aes(x=maxs[mins$origin==airport,]$date, y=maxs[mins$origin==airport,]$x, color = "Max"))
    line_mean <- geom_line(means[mins$origin==airport,], mapping = aes(x=means[mins$origin==airport,]$date, y=means[mins$origin==airport,]$x, color = "Mean"))
    labels <- labs(x = "Date", y = "Delay [minutes]", colour = NULL)
    
    p <- p + line_min + line_max + line_mean + themes + ggtitle(airport) + labels
    print(p)

3) Assuming the distance flew by the plane is, at first approximation, the distance between the two connecting airports (as given in the data frame), compute the average speed of each plane. Produce a plot of the average plane speed as a function of departure day of the year¶

In [25]:
#Distance is written in miles, air_time is in minutes --> let's convert to km/h
flights <- flights %>% add_column(speed_kmh = flights$distance*1.60934/(flights$air_time/60))
In [26]:
#Plot of average speed as function of departure day
avg_speed <- aggregate(flights$speed_kmh,list(date = flights$date),function(x) return(mean(x,na.rm=TRUE)))

p <- ggplot() + geom_line(aes(x = avg_speed$date, y = avg_speed$x), color = "firebrick") + themes + labels + ggtitle("Average flight speed")

4) - Find the airline companies offering the largest two numbers of flights per day and per week¶

Per day:¶
In [27]:
airlines_per_day <- count(flights, carrier, date) #Count flights per day and per company

find_two_max<-function(x){
    indices <- order(x$n)
    return(tail(x$carrier[indices],2))
}

#Apply find_two_max function, grouping rows by date
max_per_day <- airlines_per_day %>% group_by(date) %>% do(data.frame(maxCarrier=find_two_max(.))) 

#Tidy up data
max_per_day <- max_per_day %>% add_column(maxCarrier2 = c(tail(max_per_day$maxCarrier,length(max_per_day$maxCarrier)-1), head(max_per_day$maxCarrier,1))) %>% distinct(.,date, .keep_all=TRUE)

#Add columns with number of flights, for future plotting
max_per_day <- max_per_day %>% add_column(max = aggregate(airlines_per_day$n, list(airlines_per_day$date), max)$x)
max_per_day <- max_per_day %>% add_column(max2 = aggregate(airlines_per_day$n, list(airlines_per_day$date), function(x) max(x[-order(x)[length(x)]]))$x)
